<p>
Learning numeric prefixes is a vital step in the road to Emacs
mastery, and it's probably one of the editor's least appreciated
features. It took me more than a year to get the hang of doing
<kbd>C-3 C-k</kbd> instead of <kbd>C-a C-space C-n C-n
C-n C-w</kbd>.
</p>

<p>
Still, having three different ways of invoking this marvel is
one-too-many for my taste, specially when they take up premium
keyboard space. <kbd>M-9</kbd> isn't just a nice key, it's a
key I can hit while drunk in the dark and wearing boxing gloves &#x2014;it
deserves an equally important command.
</p>

<p>
Coincidentally, <a href="http://doc.endlessparentheses.com/Fun/backward-sexp"><code>backward-sexp</code></a> and <a href="http://doc.endlessparentheses.com/Fun/forward-sexp"><code>forward-sexp</code></a> are divine commands
with abhorrent default keybinds.
</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-cl" data-lang="cl"><span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">global-set-key</span> <span class="s">&quot;\M-9&quot;</span> <span class="ss">&#39;backward-sexp</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">global-set-key</span> <span class="s">&quot;\M-0&quot;</span> <span class="ss">&#39;forward-sexp</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">global-set-key</span> <span class="s">&quot;\M-1&quot;</span> <span class="ss">&#39;delete-other-windows</span><span class="p">)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>
<kbd>C-x 1</kbd> for <a href="http://doc.endlessparentheses.com/Fun/delete-other-windows"><code>delete-other-windows</code></a> isn't quite
abhorrent, but it also deserves better.</p>

